21. What is the difference between DELETE, TRUNCATE, and DROP?

Answer

DELETE, TRUNCATE, and DROP are SQL commands used to remove data or database objects, but they work differently.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

DELETE Command

• Removes selected rows from a table
• Uses WHERE clause to filter rows
• Table structure remains unchanged
• Can be rolled back
• Slower compared to TRUNCATE

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

TRUNCATE Command

• Removes all rows from a table
• Cannot use WHERE clause
• Table structure remains unchanged
• Faster than DELETE
• Resets auto-increment values

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

DROP Command

• Completely removes the table from database
• Deletes both data and table structure
• Cannot be rolled back in most databases
• Table no longer exists after execution

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of DELETE

DELETE FROM table_name
WHERE condition;

Example

DELETE FROM employees
WHERE employee_id = 101;

Explanation

• Deletes employee whose ID is 101.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of TRUNCATE

TRUNCATE TABLE table_name;

Example

TRUNCATE TABLE employees;

Explanation

• Removes all records from employees table.
• Table structure still exists.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of DROP

DROP TABLE table_name;

Example

DROP TABLE employees;

Explanation

• Deletes entire employees table including structure and data.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_ID      Employee_Name      Department
101              Rahul              IT
102              Priya              HR
103              Arjun              Finance

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

DELETE Example

DELETE FROM employees
WHERE employee_id = 102;

Output

101      Rahul      IT
103      Arjun      Finance

Explanation

• Only Priya's record is deleted.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

TRUNCATE Example

TRUNCATE TABLE employees;

Output

Empty Table

Explanation

• All records are removed.
• Table structure remains available.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

DROP Example

DROP TABLE employees;

Output

Table Deleted

Explanation

• Entire table including data and structure is removed.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

DELETE
• Removes selected rows
• WHERE clause can be used
• Table structure remains
• Can be rolled back
• Slower performance

TRUNCATE
• Removes all rows
• WHERE clause cannot be used
• Table structure remains
• Faster performance
• Resets auto increment

DROP
• Removes entire table
• Deletes structure and data
• Table no longer exists
• Cannot be rolled back in most cases

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• DELETE is used for removing specific rows.
• TRUNCATE is used for removing all rows quickly.
• DROP is used for deleting complete table structure.
• DELETE supports WHERE clause.
• TRUNCATE and DROP are faster than DELETE.

