22. How do you handle NULL values in MySQL?

Answer

NULL in MySQL represents a missing, unknown, or undefined value.

Handling NULL values is important to avoid incorrect query results and calculation errors.

MySQL provides different functions and operators to work with NULL values.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ways to Handle NULL Values

• IS NULL
• IS NOT NULL
• IFNULL()
• COALESCE()
• NULLIF()

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using IS NULL

• Used to find rows containing NULL values.

Syntax

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IS NULL;

Example

SELECT employee_name
FROM employees
WHERE salary IS NULL;

Explanation

• Displays employees whose salary is not available.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using IS NOT NULL

• Used to find rows that do not contain NULL values.

Syntax

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IS NOT NULL;

Example

SELECT employee_name
FROM employees
WHERE salary IS NOT NULL;

Explanation

• Displays employees whose salary exists.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using IFNULL()

• Replaces NULL value with another value.

Syntax

SELECT IFNULL(column_name, replacement_value)
FROM table_name;

Example

SELECT employee_name,
IFNULL(salary, 0)
FROM employees;

Explanation

• Replaces NULL salary values with 0.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using COALESCE()

• Returns the first non-NULL value from the list.

Syntax

SELECT COALESCE(value1, value2, value3);

Example

SELECT employee_name,
COALESCE(phone_number, email, 'No Contact')
FROM employees;

Explanation

• Displays first available contact information.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using NULLIF()

• Returns NULL if two expressions are equal.

Syntax

SELECT NULLIF(expression1, expression2);

Example

SELECT NULLIF(100, 100);

Output

NULL

Explanation

• Since both values are equal, NULL is returned.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_Name      Department      Salary
Rahul              IT              60000
Priya              HR              NULL
Arjun              IT              70000
Sneha              Finance         NULL

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

IS NULL Example

SELECT employee_name
FROM employees
WHERE salary IS NULL;

Output

Priya
Sneha

Explanation

• Displays employees whose salary is NULL.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

IFNULL() Example

SELECT employee_name,
IFNULL(salary, 0)
FROM employees;

Output

Rahul      60000
Priya      0
Arjun      70000
Sneha      0

Explanation

• NULL salary values are replaced with 0.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• NULL means missing or unknown value.
• NULL is different from 0 or empty string.
• IS NULL and IS NOT NULL are commonly used.
• IFNULL() replaces NULL with another value.
• COALESCE() returns first non-NULL value.
• Proper NULL handling improves query accuracy.

