23. What is an Index, and why is it used?

Answer

An Index in MySQL is a database object used to improve the speed of data retrieval operations.

Indexes help MySQL find rows faster without scanning the entire table.

They are mainly used on columns that are frequently searched, filtered, or sorted.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Features of Index

• Improves query performance
• Speeds up data retrieval
• Reduces table scanning
• Created on one or more columns
• Uses additional storage space

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Why Index is Used

• Faster searching of records
• Improves SELECT query performance
• Helps in sorting and filtering
• Enhances JOIN operations
• Reduces execution time for large tables

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of Creating Index

CREATE INDEX index_name
ON table_name(column_name);

Example

CREATE INDEX idx_employee_name
ON employees(employee_name);

Explanation

• Creates an index on employee_name column.
• Improves search performance on employee_name.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of Viewing Index

SHOW INDEX FROM table_name;

Example

SHOW INDEX FROM employees;

Explanation

• Displays all indexes created on employees table.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of Dropping Index

DROP INDEX index_name
ON table_name;

Example

DROP INDEX idx_employee_name
ON employees;

Explanation

• Removes index from employee_name column.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table with thousands of records.

Employee_ID      Employee_Name      Department
101              Rahul              IT
102              Priya              HR
103              Arjun              Finance

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Without Index

SELECT * FROM employees
WHERE employee_name = 'Rahul';

Explanation

• MySQL scans entire table row by row.
• Query execution becomes slower for large tables.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

With Index

CREATE INDEX idx_employee_name
ON employees(employee_name);

SELECT * FROM employees
WHERE employee_name = 'Rahul';

Explanation

• MySQL uses index to quickly locate records.
• Query execution becomes much faster.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Types of Indexes

Primary Index
• Automatically created on PRIMARY KEY

Unique Index
• Prevents duplicate values

Composite Index
• Created on multiple columns

Full-Text Index
• Used for text searching

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Advantages of Index

• Faster data retrieval
• Improves query optimization
• Better performance for large databases
• Faster sorting and filtering

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Disadvantages of Index

• Uses extra storage space
• Slows down INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE operations
• Too many indexes reduce performance

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• Index improves SELECT query speed.
• Mostly used on frequently searched columns.
• Indexes increase database performance.
• Excessive indexes can slow data modification operations.
• PRIMARY KEY automatically creates an index.

