24. Explain the difference between a Clustered and Non-Clustered Index.

Answer

Clustered and Non-Clustered Indexes are used to improve database performance and speed up data retrieval, but they store data differently.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Clustered Index

• Stores actual table data in sorted order
• Changes physical order of rows in table
• Table can have only one Clustered Index
• Faster for range-based searches
• PRIMARY KEY usually creates Clustered Index

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Non-Clustered Index

• Stores index separately from actual table data
• Contains pointers to data rows
• Does not change physical order of table
• Multiple Non-Clustered Indexes can exist
• Slightly slower compared to Clustered Index

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Clustered Index Syntax

CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX index_name
ON table_name(column_name);

Example

CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX idx_employee_id
ON employees(employee_id);

Explanation

• Arranges table records physically based on employee_id.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Non-Clustered Index Syntax

CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX index_name
ON table_name(column_name);

Example

CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX idx_employee_name
ON employees(employee_name);

Explanation

• Creates separate index structure for employee_name.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_ID      Employee_Name      Department
101              Rahul              IT
102              Priya              HR
103              Arjun              Finance
104              Sneha              IT

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Clustered Index Example

CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX idx_employee_id
ON employees(employee_id);

Explanation

• Records are physically stored in sorted order of employee_id.
• Searching employee by ID becomes faster.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Non-Clustered Index Example

CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX idx_employee_name
ON employees(employee_name);

Explanation

• Separate index table stores employee_name with pointers to actual rows.
• Searching by employee_name becomes faster.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

Clustered Index
• Stores actual data rows
• Changes physical order of table
• Only one allowed per table
• Faster retrieval performance
• Usually created on PRIMARY KEY

Non-Clustered Index
• Stores pointers to data
• Does not change physical order
• Multiple indexes allowed
• Slightly slower than clustered
• Used for frequently searched columns

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Advantages of Clustered Index

• Faster data retrieval
• Efficient for range queries
• Better performance for sorting

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Advantages of Non-Clustered Index

• Multiple indexes allowed
• Improves search on different columns
• Does not affect physical table structure

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• Clustered Index stores actual table data.
• Non-Clustered Index stores references to data.
• A table can have only one Clustered Index.
• A table can have multiple Non-Clustered Indexes.
• Both indexes improve query performance.

