26. What is a Trigger?

Answer

A Trigger in MySQL is a stored program that automatically executes when a specific event occurs on a table.

Triggers are activated automatically during INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE operations.

They are mainly used for auditing, validation, logging, and maintaining data integrity.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Features of Trigger

• Executes automatically
• Associated with a table
• Activated by INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE events
• Helps maintain data consistency
• Used for automation in database operations

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Types of Triggers

BEFORE INSERT Trigger
• Executes before inserting data

AFTER INSERT Trigger
• Executes after inserting data

BEFORE UPDATE Trigger
• Executes before updating data

AFTER UPDATE Trigger
• Executes after updating data

BEFORE DELETE Trigger
• Executes before deleting data

AFTER DELETE Trigger
• Executes after deleting data

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of Trigger

CREATE TRIGGER trigger_name
BEFORE | AFTER
INSERT | UPDATE | DELETE
ON table_name
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN
    trigger_statements;
END;

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Example of Trigger

CREATE TRIGGER before_employee_insert
BEFORE INSERT
ON employees
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN
    SET NEW.salary = IFNULL(NEW.salary, 0);
END;

Explanation

• Automatically sets salary to 0 if NULL value is inserted.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_ID      Employee_Name      Salary
101              Rahul              60000
102              Priya              45000

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Trigger Example

CREATE TRIGGER employee_log
AFTER INSERT
ON employees
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN
    INSERT INTO employee_audit
    VALUES (NEW.employee_id, 'New Employee Added');
END;

Explanation

• Whenever a new employee is inserted,
  a log entry is automatically added into employee_audit table.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

INSERT Example

INSERT INTO employees
VALUES (103, 'Arjun', 70000);

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Output in employee_audit Table

103      New Employee Added

Explanation

• Trigger automatically executes after INSERT operation.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Advantages of Triggers

• Automates database tasks
• Maintains data integrity
• Helps in auditing and logging
• Reduces manual operations
• Enforces business rules

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Disadvantages of Triggers

• Can slow database performance
• Difficult to debug
• Hidden execution may confuse developers
• Excessive triggers increase complexity

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• Trigger executes automatically on table events.
• Used with INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE operations.
• BEFORE and AFTER are common trigger types.
• Helps maintain consistency and automation.
• Trigger is associated with a specific table.

