27. What is a Stored Procedure?

Answer

A Stored Procedure in MySQL is a collection of SQL statements stored in the database that can be executed repeatedly.

Stored Procedures help reduce code duplication and improve performance by reusing SQL logic.

They are mainly used for automation, business logic, and complex database operations.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Features of Stored Procedure

• Collection of SQL statements
• Stored inside database
• Can be executed multiple times
• Improves performance
• Reduces repeated SQL code

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Why Stored Procedures are Used

• Reuse SQL code
• Improve database performance
• Reduce network traffic
• Simplify complex operations
• Maintain business logic in database

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of Stored Procedure

DELIMITER //

CREATE PROCEDURE procedure_name()
BEGIN
    SQL statements;
END //

DELIMITER ;

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Example of Stored Procedure

DELIMITER //

CREATE PROCEDURE GetEmployees()
BEGIN
    SELECT * FROM employees;
END //

DELIMITER ;

Explanation

• Creates a stored procedure named GetEmployees.
• Displays all employee records when executed.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Executing Stored Procedure

CALL GetEmployees();

Explanation

• Executes the stored procedure.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_ID      Employee_Name      Department      Salary
101              Rahul              IT              60000
102              Priya              HR              45000
103              Arjun              Finance         70000

