30. What is the difference between the = and LIKE operators?

Answer

The = operator and LIKE operator are used in MySQL to compare values, but they work differently.

The = operator checks for exact matches, whereas the LIKE operator is used for pattern matching.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

= Operator

• Used for exact value comparison
• Matches complete value exactly
• Cannot perform pattern matching
• Faster than LIKE in most cases

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LIKE Operator

• Used for pattern matching
• Searches partial matches
• Works with wildcard characters
• Commonly used in text searching

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Wildcard Characters in LIKE

% Symbol
• Represents zero or more characters

_ Symbol
• Represents a single character

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of = Operator

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name = value;

Example

SELECT *
FROM employees
WHERE department = 'IT';

Explanation

• Displays employees whose department is exactly IT.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of LIKE Operator

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name LIKE pattern;

Example

SELECT *
FROM employees
WHERE employee_name LIKE 'R%';

Explanation

• Displays employee names starting with letter R.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_Name      Department
Rahul              IT
Priya              HR
Ramesh             Finance
Arjun              IT
Rohit              HR

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

= Operator Example

SELECT *
FROM employees
WHERE department = 'IT';

Output

Rahul      IT
Arjun      IT

Explanation

• Only rows with exact department value IT are displayed.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LIKE Operator Example

SELECT *
FROM employees
WHERE employee_name LIKE 'R%';

Output

Rahul
Ramesh
Rohit

Explanation

• Displays employee names starting with R.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LIKE with % Wildcard

SELECT *
FROM employees
WHERE employee_name LIKE '%a%';

Explanation

• Displays names containing letter a.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LIKE with _ Wildcard

SELECT *
FROM employees
WHERE employee_name LIKE '_a%';

Explanation

• Displays names where second letter is a.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

= Operator
• Exact value matching
• No wildcard support
• Faster performance
• Used for precise comparison

LIKE Operator
• Pattern matching
• Supports wildcards
• Slightly slower
• Used for searching patterns

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• = operator checks exact matches only.
• LIKE operator performs pattern matching.
• % represents multiple characters.
• _ represents single character.
• LIKE is commonly used for searching text data.

